## Arrays

An array stores multiple values in a single variable.

```javascript
let cities = ["Pune", "Mumbai", "Nagpur"];
```

### Array Index

```text
0 → Pune
1 → Mumbai
2 → Nagpur
```

---

## Array Length

```javascript
cities.length
```

Returns the number of items in the array.

Example:

```javascript
let cities = ["Pune", "Mumbai", "Nagpur"];

console.log(cities.length);
```

Output:

```text
3
```

---

## innerHTML

```javascript
element.innerHTML
```

Used to add or modify HTML content.

Example:

```javascript
list.innerHTML = "<li>Pune</li>";
```

Creates:

```html
<li>Pune</li>
```

inside the webpage.

---

## Loop Through an Array

```javascript
for(let i = 0; i < cities.length; i++) {
    console.log(cities[i]);
}
```

Output:

```text
Pune
Mumbai
Nagpur
```

---

## Display Array Data on a Webpage

HTML:

```html
<ul id="cityList"></ul>
```

JavaScript:

```javascript
let cities = ["Pune", "Mumbai", "Nagpur"];

let cityList =
document.querySelector("#cityList");

for(let i = 0; i < cities.length; i++) {

    cityList.innerHTML +=
    `<li>${cities[i]}</li>`;

}
```

Output:

```text
• Pune
• Mumbai
• Nagpur
```

---

## Why Use += ?

```javascript
list.innerHTML +=
```

Adds new content while keeping existing content.

Without `+=`, previous content gets replaced.

---

## Key Takeaways

- Arrays store multiple values.
- `length` returns the size of an array.
- Loops help process array items.
- `innerHTML` creates HTML content.
- `+=` appends content instead of replacing it.

